Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in generating diverse yet high-quality solutions—especially in AI-driven design, planning, or generative modeling—lies in balancing two competing objectives: maintaining functional optimality within a solution (intra-diversity robustness) while ensuring meaningful differences across solutions (inter-diversity separation). Existing methods often treat diversity as a post-hoc filtering step or rely on heuristic distance metrics that lack semantic grounding. Inspired by Paper 1’s emphasis on disentangling processes and Paper 2’s lattice-theoretic formulation of structured selection, I propose a novel framework that geometrically regulates diversity directly in the latent space using *learned semantic manifolds*. Unlike prior work that uses Euclidean or cosine distances, this approach leverages curvature-aware constraints derived from task-specific performance landscapes to define *feasible solution tubes* (intra-constraints) and *repulsive semantic cones* (inter-constraints). This ensures that all generated solutions remain near-optimal under perturbation (robustness), while being separated along semantically meaningful, non-degenerate directions (e.g., different strategies, configurations, or modes). The integration of differential geometry with structured optimization on latent lattices enables formal guarantees on both quality and diversity—a gap not addressed in Papers 1–3, which focus on reasoning disentanglement or submodular selection without joint diversity-optimality control.

